{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505782"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:35:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2481"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2481"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.1,0.77,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76918"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2481"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10338"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76918"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 48-hour history of fevers and difficulty breathing. She is a resident of a nursing home. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and confused. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 91% on room air, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. She has dry mucous membranes. Her chest examination reveals bilateral lower zone crackles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 18 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.5-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray: bilateral lower zone opacification\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 70 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is diagnosed with bacterial pneumonia and treated with oxygen, fluid resuscitation and intravenous antibiotics. While her haemodynamic status improves over 48 hours, her eGFR falls to 25 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Urinalysis shows muddy brown casts, renal tubular epithelial cells, and proteinuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely finding on renal biopsy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal findings","Post-infectious glomerulonephritis","Acute tubular necrosis","Goodpasture syndrome","IgA nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of acute tubular necrosis (ATN) in the setting of sepsis and hypotension. \u003Cstrong\u003EAcute tubular necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of intrinsic acute kidney injury, particularly in hospitalised patients. The diagnosis is supported by the acute decline in renal function and characteristic urinalysis findings of muddy brown casts and renal tubular epithelial cells. On biopsy, ATN shows tubular cell necrosis, loss of brush border, and tubular dilatation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal findings\u003C/strong\u003E would be inconsistent with the significant decline in renal function and abnormal urinalysis findings seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-infectious glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs following streptococcal infections and presents with different urinalysis findings, including red cell casts. The timing and pattern of renal dysfunction in this case is more consistent with ATN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoodpasture syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E causes a pulmonary-renal syndrome with anti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies. While this patient has both respiratory and renal involvement, the clinical context of sepsis and shock makes ATN more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with episodes of visible haematuria concurrent with upper respiratory tract infections. The urinalysis findings and acute nature of the renal dysfunction are not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key features supporting ATN in this case are the presence of risk factors (hypotension, sepsis), timing of renal dysfunction (acute decline over 48 hours), and characteristic urinalysis findings. ATN is often reversible with supportive care once the underlying cause is addressed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute tubular necrosis (ATN) is characterised by muddy brown casts and renal tubular epithelial cells on urinalysis.","Hypotension and sepsis are common causes of ischaemic acute tubular necrosis.","Acute tubular necrosis typically shows acute decline in renal function over hours to days."],"references":["Esson ML, Schrier RW. Diagnosis and treatment of acute tubular necrosis. Ann Intern Med. 2002;137(9):744-52. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12416948/","Hanif MO, Bali A, Ramphul K. Acute Renal Tubular Necrosis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507815/","Perazella MA, Coca SG, Hall IE, Iyanam U, Koraishy M, Parikh CR. Urine microscopy is associated with severity and worsening of acute kidney injury in hospitalized patients. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2010;5(3):402-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20089493/","Perazella MA, Coca SG, Kanbay M, Brewster UC, Parikh CR. Diagnostic value of urine microscopy for differential diagnosis of acute kidney injury in hospitalized patients. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008;3(6):1615-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18784207/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2481"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:31:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T20:31:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2481"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76918"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"c